            "id": "fc0df405eaf34a1a933c0",
            "questionText": "A massive rocket launches from Earth, expelling hot gases downwards at an extremely high velocity. Consider a rocket with an initial mass of $!$2.0 \\times 10^5 \\text{ kg}$!$ that expels hot gases at a constant exhaust velocity of $!$2500 \\text{ m/s}$!$, with a mass flow rate of $!$500 \\text{ kg/s}$!$. Assuming the rocket starts from rest and neglecting gravitational effects, calculate the numerical magnitude of the average resultant force exerted on the rocket during the initial $!$10 \\text{ seconds}$!$ of its launch.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "cbd5cdc43a5d49d681f36",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by recalling how we define the average resultant force in terms of momentum. Identify the correct equation that relates force to the rate of change of momentum.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "1a227599-b55c-4dde-ab9a-1062a5fb942c",
                        "eb2f76a7-4c38-468d-b7dd-2f8dc4135942"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F=\\frac{\\Delta p}{\\Delta t}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F= m\\times a$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F=\\frac{mv}{t}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F=\\frac{\\Delta(mv)}{m\\Delta t}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "b4060306a4c84b7e836b9",
                    "stepText": "Next, determine the expression for the momentum change per second due to the mass being expelled. Which equation correctly represents the rate at which momentum is being imparted by the expelled gases?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "eb2f76a7-4c38-468d-b7dd-2f8dc4135942",
                        "04c41e33-e440-4c28-98c2-3bb76709f5f6"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\dot{m}\\,v_{exhaust}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\dot{m}^2\\,v_{exhaust}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\dot{m} + v_{exhaust}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\frac{\\dot{m}}{v_{exhaust}}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "a8892dfe9b2c4100ba02a",
                    "stepText": "Now, using the established expression, calculate the product of the mass flow rate and the exhaust velocity. Enter the numerical value you obtain.",
